<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n30161g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n30" href="#n30161g">N30 (VI.B.22)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n30all.htm#n30161g"> 161(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> trance narcolepsy / (transitio, transivi)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Every now and again reports are made of persons, usually young women, entering upon very prolonged periods of sleep. This condition is called <mark>trance or narcolepsy</mark>. It is allied physiologically to hibernation or the winter sleep of animals. The word &ldquo;trance&rdquo; is the English form of &ldquo;transitium&rdquo;, a going over, from &ldquo;transire&rdquo;, to go across, a late-Latin but quite poetical expression for dying. <small> D. F. Fraser-Harris, <a name="FHMS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FHMS"><cite title="source">Morpheus, or: The Future of Sleep</cite></a> (1928) 38</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c13240f" href="c13all.htm#c13240f">VI.C.13:240(f)</a>, <a name="c13240g" href="c13all.htm#c13240g">VI.C.13:240(g)</a>, <a name="c13240h" href="c13all.htm#c13240h">VI.C.13:240(h)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
